      textEn: [
        "Two bright dots appeared in the clear night sky, drawing closer until we could see they were one red and one green light. Then came a rumbling \u2014 an aircraft flying at night. How does a plane fly safely in pitch darkness? To understand this secret, we begin with bats.",
        "Bats can fly at night and even catch moths and mosquitoes; moreover, no matter how they fly, they have never been seen to collide with anything \u2014 even an extremely thin wire can be nimbly dodged. Could their eyes be so sharp that they can see everything clearly in the pitch-dark night?",
        "To figure out this question, over two hundred years ago scientists conducted an experiment. They strung many ropes crisscross through a room and tied many bells to the ropes, then blindfolded a bat and let it fly around inside the room. The bat flew for several hours, and not a single bell rang \u2014 among all those ropes, it had not touched a single one.",
        "Scientists ran two more experiments: one with the bat\u2019s ears plugged, another with its mouth sealed. The bat bumped around like a headless fly, and the bells rang non-stop.",
        "The results of the three experiments proved that bats fly at night not by relying on their eyes, but by coordinating their mouths and ears to find their way. Later, after repeated research, scientists finally unveiled the secret of how bats can fly at night. As a bat flies, it emits ultrasound from its mouth. This sound cannot be heard by human ears, but bats\u2019 ears can hear it. When the ultrasound travels forward and encounters an obstacle, it reflects back and reaches the bat\u2019s ears, and the bat immediately changes its flight direction.",
        "Now that you know how bats fly at night, can you guess the airplane\u2019s secret? Modern planes are equipped with radar, which works on a similar principle. Radar sends radio waves via an antenna; these bounce off obstacles and return to the radar receiver, appearing on a fluorescent screen. Pilots can clearly see whether obstacles lie ahead, making flight much safer."
      ],
